**2. Wire it up in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Add Problem Details + custom handler
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<GlobalExceptionHandler>();

var app = builder.Build();

// Must come before endpoint mapping
app.UseExceptionHandler();

app.MapGet("/example/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    if (id < 0) throw new ArgumentException("ID must be positive");
    if (id == 0) throw new KeyNotFoundException("Item not found");
    return Results.Ok(new { Id = id });
});

app.Run();
```

**How it works:**

- `IExceptionHandler` (available since .NET 8) is invoked by the built-in `UseExceptionHandler()` middleware — no per-endpoint try-catch needed.
- The switch expression maps exception types to status codes.
- For 500s, the actual exception message is suppressed to avoid leaking internals; only `"An unexpected error occurred."` is returned.
- All responses use the `ProblemDetails` shape (`application/json` with `status`, `title`, `detail` fields per RFC 7807).
